# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cannon
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The **11th Marine Regiment** is an artillery regiment of the United States Marine Corps based at Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton, California.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Known as the "Cannon Cockers", the regiment falls under the command of the 1st Marine Division and the I Marine Expeditionary Force.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Its primary weapon system is the M777A2 howitzer with a maximum effective range of 30 km, however the 5th Battalion has converted to fire the HIMARS (High Mobility Artillery Rocket System) weapon system.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The 11th Marine Regiment was activated during World War I on 3 January 1918.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Originally planned as a light artillery regiment, it was converted to an infantry unit and went to France as part of the 5th Marine Expeditionary Brigade in the waning days of the war.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] It did not see combat, but served as base guard troops and returned home to be disbanded on 11 August 1919.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] On 9 May 1927, another 11th Regiment was activated from troops in Haiti and at Quantico for service in Nicaragua of brief duration.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The regimental headquarters was disbanded on 31 July 1927, and the two battalions in September.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Renewed political problems in Nicaragua and the intensified guerrilla campaign of the bandit leader Augusto Sandino caused the activation of another 11th Regiment at Norfolk, Virginia, and San Diego, California, in January 1928.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] A third battalion was organized on the east coast on 21 March 1928.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Again, service in Nicaragua was brief, with the third battalion being disbanded on 15 June 1929 and the remainder of the regiment on 31 August 1929.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] With the approach of World War II and the consequent expansion of the Marine Corps, an 11th Marines (Artillery) was activated at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, on 1 March 1941.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Activation of the regiment's organic battalions already had been underway since 1 September 1940 when the 1st Battalion was created.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] After its return to the United States from Cuba, the regiment (less the 1st Battalion) shipped overseas with the 1st Marine Division to New Zealand in June–July 1942.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The 1st Battalion went to Samoa with the 7th Marine Regiment in March 1942.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Together they formed the 3rd Marine Brigade until they were sent to Guadalcanal that fall.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The 11th Marines participated in the Battle of Guadalcanal in August with the 1st Marine Division and played an especially significant part in the Battle of the Tenaru and the Battle of Bloody Ridge.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The 1st Battalion rejoined the regiment in September on Guadalcanal.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] On 15 December 1942, the 11th Marines left Guadalcanal for Australia, rested and reorganized, and then reentered combat on New Britain at Cape Gloucester on 26 December 1943.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Here the regiment furnished support to the infantry in their capture of the Japanese aerodrome.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Following the New Britain campaign came a period of preparation for the Peleliu landing where the regiment was actively engaged.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] For the first two weeks after the initial landing on 15 September 1944, the regiment took part in the Battle of Peleliu under Colonel William H.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] All artillery support was handled both novelly and conventionally, providing massed preparatory, harassing, and interdicting fire.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Later, the artillery was used to fire directly into the mouths of enemy caves.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] In March 1945, the 11th Marines participated in the Battle of Okinawa, its final combat operation of World War II.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] There the regiment played an important defensive role with effective counter-battery fire, and steadily suppressed enemy attempts to counter-attack objectives already won by U.S. forces.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] With the war won, in the fall of 1945 the 11th Marines moved to Tianjin in North China as an element of Operation Beleaguer.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] There it was soon involved in trying to keep peace in the midst of the increasing conflict between rival Chinese factions.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Early in 1947, the regiment returned to the United States to be reduced virtually to a battalion-sized unit.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Three years later North Korea invaded South Korea, and the 1st Battalion was part of the 1st Provisional Marine Brigade deployed in August 1950 to the Pusan Perimeter to help stem their advance.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Other battalions were organized in the United States and were available for service when the 1st Marine Division made the Incheon landing.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Shifted back to the east coast of Korea, the battalions were attached to regimental combat teams and participated in the Battle of Chosin Reservoir.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] One of the more famous engagements of the regiment during the Korean War came on 7 December 1950 during the breakout from the Chosin Reservoir.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] George and How Batteries of 2nd Battalion were halted along the main road by heavy machine gun fire.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The ensuing fight would pit two artillery batteries against a battalion of Chinese infantry in broad daylight and at close range.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The guns were laid level due to the proximity of the Chinese forces and the Marines braced their bodies against the guns because there was no time to dig them in.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] When it was over the Marines counted over 500 enemy dead on the field and had expended over 600 rounds of ammunition.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The 11th Marines participated in continued heavy action on the East Central Front throughout 1951, (such as the Battle of the Punchbowl) and in March 1952, moved to the Western Front, (Battle of Bunker Hill near Panmunjom).
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The 11th was finally able to sail from Korea for the United States and Camp Pendleton on 7 March 1955.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The years between 1955 and 1965 were spent in continued training to maintain a constant state of readiness.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] During the Cuban Missile Crisis of October 1962, the 11th Marines played a role in the task force ordered to impose a naval quarantine against arms shipments to Cuba.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] A new era opened on 8 March 1965 when the Marines were committed to ground action in South Vietnam.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Beginning on 16 August 1965, the regiment was gradually deployed to South Vietnam.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The transfer was completed by the arrival of the 2d Battalion on 27 May 1966.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The nature of the war required the artillerymen to defend their own positions against numerous enemy probes and brought about a vastly increased employment of artillery by helicopters, both for displacement and resupply.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The regimental history in Vietnam was characterized by fighting as detachments in dispersed areas.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Hastings, Hue City, Napoleon/Saline II, Mameluke Thrust, Oklahoma Hills, Pipestone Canyon and Imperial Lake were some of the more significant operations in which the regiment participated.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Redeployment to the United States started in October 1970.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The 1st Battalion was the last unit of the regiment to depart for the United States and Camp Pendleton in May 1971.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] During the next decade, the 11th Marines experienced a high level of activity, participating in many training and support exercises.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] In 1975 the regiment provided support for Operation New Arrivals and the Vietnamese refugees.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The 11th Marines participated in numerous training exercises throughout the 1980s to maintain the regiments high level of operational readiness.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The regiment's ability to respond quickly to a crisis was put to the test in August 1990, when Iraq invaded and occupied its neighbor, Kuwait.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Bush immediately ordered American forces, including Marines, to the Persian Gulf, to deter a possible Iraqi assault into Saudi Arabia.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Elements of the 11th Marines began departing Camp Pendleton on 25 August as part of the 7th Marine Expeditionary Brigade, en route to Saudi Arabia and Operation Desert Shield.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Early in September, 7th MEB was absorbed by I Marine Expeditionary Force.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The mission of the 11th Marines was to provide effective artillery support to the various task forces comprising the 1st Marine Division.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Upon arrival in Saudi Arabia, the regiment began an intensive training program, which included liaison with the famous British "Desert Rats," the 40th Field Regiment Royal Artillery.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Operation Desert Storm began early on 17 January 1991, and the 11th Marines fired its first artillery mission against Iraqi forces, when elements of the regiment conducted an early morning surface artillery raid just south of Khafji.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] This was the first in a series of 11th Marines artillery raids conducted along the Saudi Arabian/Kuwaiti border, both on the Persian Gulf coast and along the south-west border area near several oil fields.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] As the major coalition ground offensive began on 24 February, the 11th Marines was already inside Kuwait providing vital fire support to Task Forces Grizzly and Taro.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Throughout Operation Desert Storm, the 11th Marines provided close and continuous fire support to the 1st Marine Division.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Upon 28 February 1991 ceasefire which ended the fighting, the 11th Marines prepared to leave the Persian Gulf for home.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The regiment's seven-month deployment and the Gulf War came to an end on 5 April with a much-deserved welcome at Camp Pendleton, California.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Throughout the remaining years of the decade, elements of the 11th Marines participated in Operation Sea Angel in Bangladesh and in Operation Restore Hope in Somalia.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The regiment also assisted in fire-fighting efforts in the western United States during the summer of 1994.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The terrorist attacks on 11 September 2001 marked the start of the global war on terror.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The Cannon Cockers were ready when the order was given to deploy.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Beginning in 2003, the 11th Marine Regiment actively participated in Operations Enduring Freedom and Iraqi Freedom.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] This included deploying as a regiment to Kuwait and Iraq in January–May 2003.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] From 2004 to 2009, elements from the Regiment deployed in support of all major contingency operations in Iraq and Afghanistan.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] In 2009, the world's focus shifted towards the Afghanistan area of operations.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] From 2009 to present day, Cannon Cocker batteries have supported Operation Enduring Freedom without any lapse in coverage.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Most recently, elements of the 11th Marine Regiment participated in the fight against the Islamic State in Syria as a part of Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] The Commanding Officer of 11th Marines is Colonel Benjamin B.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] A unit citation or commendation is an award bestowed upon an organization for the action cited.
[src:cannon/11th-marine-regiment] Members of the unit who participated in said actions are allowed to wear on their uniforms the appropriate ribbon of the awarded unit citation.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The social reforms of the French Revolution had been well received by the majority of the populace of France, but the Revolution's strongly anti-Catholic stance had created anti-Republican sympathies in many Roman Catholics.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] In March 1793, this sentiment boiled over into an armed insurrection in the fiercely Catholic Vendée region of western France.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] A rebel army titled *Armée catholique et royale* now proved to be a thorn in the side of the Revolutionary government in Paris, under leaders such as François de Charette de la Contrie and Maurice d'Elbée.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The rebels were known as *Chouans*, a title which comes from early Royalist leader Jean Cottereau's nickname Jean Chouan.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The *Armée catholique et royale* quickly garnered British support and got off to a promising start, severely defeating several Revolutionary Armies.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The Revolutionary Committee of Public Safety ordered General Jean-Baptiste Carrier to pacify the region, and over several months Carrier ruthlessly suppressed the Vendée.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The local population dubbed Carrier's forces the infernal columns.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] On 22 December 1793, the Chouan rebellion subsided following a major defeat at the Battle of Savenay.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Following the 9th Thermidor, those Chouans willing to lay down arms were granted amnesty by the reformed National Convention.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The Chouans responded by attacking the Republican-held town of Guémené-sur-Scorff on 28 January 1795.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The Convention immediately ordered General Louis Lazare Hoche to proceed to the Vendée and force the Chouans to agree to a cessation of hostilities.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Hoche quickly defeated the Chouan army and on 17 February François de Charette de la Contrie signed a very generous peace settlement.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] A small contingent of Royalists under the command of General Jean-Nicolas Stofflet and the fanatical Etienne-Alexandre Bernier refused to accept the peace settlement and continued to offer resistance to Hoche's army.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] They were supported by the British in the form of 4,000 émigrés.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] This large force was placed under the command of émigré Générals Joseph de Puisaye and Hermilly.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Hearing of this, de Charette de la Contrie broke the peace agreement and reopened hostilities.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] On 26 June, the émigré force landed at Carnac.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Hermilly quickly advanced on Auray before engaging and being defeated by Hoche at Vannes.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] By early July, Hermilly had been forced out of Auray and was besieged in the Fortress of Penthièvre.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] This meant that the entire insurgent army was now trapped on the Quiberon peninsula.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] On 15 July, an additional émigré division arrived to bolster the defense, under the command of Général Charles François de Virot de Sombreuil, but Hermilly was killed in action on 16 July.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] By the 20th, the fortress had fallen and Hoche swiftly advanced down the peninsula, defeating the hopelessly trapped émigré army.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Only Général Puisaye and a small force were able to escape with the British fleet; the remainder were killed in action, taken prisoner, or executed.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Despite the failure of the émigré army, de Charette de la Contrie continued to offer resistance.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] In early September, a popular revolt broke out in the area around Dreux, but it was defeated in battle at Nonancourt.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] De Charette de la Contrie himself suffered a major defeat at Saint-Cyr on 25 September.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Despite this, the Comte d'Artois landed at Île d'Yeu with 1,000 émigrés and 2,000 British troops.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Bolstered by this force, the Royalist troops began marching on Paris in early October 1795.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The arrival of the Comte d'Artois excited the *jeunesse dorée* Royalist supporters in the Le Peletier section of the capital (named for the Rue Le Peletier in what is now the Second Arrondissement), and they began demonstrations in the form of felling Liberty Trees and trampling cockades of France.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Rumours began to circulate regarding the likely defection of the entire Paris National Guard.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The Convention quickly realised that it was in severe danger, and that an enemy force was on French soil; indeed, the insurrection in Paris meant that there was now an enemy force within the capital itself.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The Convention declared its intention to remain in their meeting rooms until the crisis was resolved.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] It called for the formation of three battalions of Patriots to be raised from the Jacobin military staff dismissed after 9 Thermidor.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Général Jean-François, baron de Menou was given command of the defence of the capital, but he was severely outnumbered with only 5,000 troops on hand to resist the Royalist army of 25,000 men.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] On 12 Vendémiaire (4 October 1795), the National Guard arrived in Le Peletier in an attempt to put down the unrest.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The Military Committee of the Sections of the Capital under the command of Jean-Thomas-Élisabeth Richer de Sérizy announced that the decrees of the convention were no longer recognised.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Général Louis Michel Auguste Thévenet (called Danican) took command of the National Guard in the Le Peletier section.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The Convention ordered Menou to advance into Le Peletier, to disarm the entire area, and to close Danican's headquarters.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Generals Despierres and Verdière were sent to Menou to assist him.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Menou divided his force into three columns and planned an advance into Le Peletier on the evening of 12 Vendémiaire.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] When the advance was set to begin, Despierres reported that he was unwell and unable to proceed, and Verdière refused to advance.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Menou timidly advanced towards the Royalist force, inviting the rebels to discuss terms of their dispersal.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] He withdrew after receiving the insurgents' promise to disarm.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The Le Peletier section, seeing this as a sign of weakness on the part of the convention, called upon the other sections of Paris to rise up.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Menou realised his mistake, and launched a cavalry attack down the Rue du Faubourg-Montmartre, temporarily clearing the area of Royalists.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The Convention dismissed Menou from the command and ordered Paul François Jean Nicolas Barras to take over the defence of the convention.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Young General Napoleon Bonaparte was aware of the commotion, and he arrived at the Convention around this time to find out what was happening.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] He was quickly ordered to join Barras' forces mustering for the defence of the Republic.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Bonaparte accepted, but only on the condition that he was granted complete freedom of movement.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] At 1 am on 13 Vendémiaire (5 October), Bonaparte overrode Barras, who was content to let him do as he wished.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Bonaparte ordered Joachim Murat, a sous-lieutenant in the *12ème Régiment de Chasseurs à Cheval*, to ride to the plain of Sablons and to return with the 40 cannon which Menou had indicated were located there.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Murat's squadron retrieved the cannons before the Royalists arrived and Bonaparte organised their arrangement, placing them in commanding areas with effective fields of fire.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The Republican forces were outnumbered approximately 6 to 1, but they held their perimeter all the same.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] At 5 am, a probing attack by the Royalist forces was repulsed.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Five hours later, the major Royalist assault by 7,000 men began.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The Republican forces held their perimeter, the cannons firing grapeshot into the massed Royalist forces.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The Patriot battalions supporting the artillery also cut down the advancing Royalist ranks.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Bonaparte commanded throughout the two-hour engagement, and survived unscathed despite having his horse shot from under him.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The effect of the grapeshot and the volleys from the Patriot forces caused the Royalist attack to waver.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Bonaparte ordered a counterattack led by Murat's squadron of chasseurs.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] At the close of the battle, around three hundred Royalists lay dead on the streets of Paris.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The defeat of the Royalist insurrection extinguished the threat to the convention.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] On 19 October all the officers in the army, also the ones who were dismissed, had to prove for the Committee of Public Safety where they were on the days around 13 Vendémiaire.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] On Sunday 25 October the National Convention declared itself dissolved and voted for a general amnesty for "deeds exclusively connected with the Revolution".
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Not long after the Directoire and Council of Five Hundred was installed; the Committee of Public Safety disappeared.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Napoleon was appointed as General in Chief of the Army of the Interior.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Bonaparte became a national hero, and was quickly promoted to Général de Division.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Within five months, he was given command of the French army conducting operations in Italy.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The defeated Royalists, in an effort to portray the Republican defense as a massacre, nicknamed Bonaparte *Général Vendémiaire*, a title which he later claimed would be his *first title of glory*.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] Abel Gance portrayed 13 Vendémiaire in act iii of his silent production *Napoléon*.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The first episode of the 2002 miniseries *Napoléon* portrays the battle of 13 Vendémiaire.
[src:cannon/13-vendémiaire] The events are also depicted in the 2023 film *Napoleon*.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Written in just 6 weeks the Overture's first public performance, conducted by Ippolit Al'tani, took place in Moscow on 20 August [O.S.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] 8 August] 1882, under a tent, near the still unfinished Cathedral of Christ the Saviour, which also memorialised the 1812 defence of Russia.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The fifteen-minute overture is best known for its climactic volley of cannon fire, ringing chimes, and a brass fanfare finale.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] It has also become a common accompaniment to fireworks displays on the United States' Independence Day.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The *1812 Overture* went on to become one of Tchaikovsky's most popular works, along with his ballet scores to *The Nutcracker*, *The Sleeping Beauty*, and *Swan Lake*.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The carillon is sometimes replaced with tubular bells or recordings of carillons, or even church bells.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] In the sections that contain cannon shots, actual cannons are sometimes replaced by howitzers, tanks, fireworks, recorded cannons, or played on a piece of staging, usually with a large wooden mallet or sledgehammer as used in Mahler's 6th Symphony.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The bass drum, and gong/tam-tam are also regularly used as cannon substitutes or adjuncts in indoor performances.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Two years later, the American conductor Igor Buketoff, son of a Russian Orthodox priest, went a stage further on his RCA Victrola recording with the New Philharmonia Orchestra.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Not only did he deploy voices for the opening chant but he also had a children's chorus sing the folk tune "By the Gates" and brought the choir back to bolster the chant and the Russian Imperial national anthem *God Save the Tsar!*.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] On 7 September 1812, at Borodino, 120 km (75 mi) west of Moscow, Napoleon's forces met those of General Mikhail Kutuzov in a concerted stand made by Russia against the seemingly invincible French Army.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The Battle of Borodino saw casualties estimated as high as 100,000 and the French were masters of the field.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] It was, however, ultimately a pyrrhic victory for the French invasion.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] With resources depleted and supply lines overextended, Napoleon's weakened forces moved into Moscow, which they occupied with no delegation to receive the conquerors.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Expecting a capitulation from Tsar Alexander I, the French instead found themselves in a barren and desolate city.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] To make things worse, 48 hours after Napoleon's entry to the Russian city on 14 September 1812, three quarters of Moscow was burned to the ground.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Deprived of winter stores, Napoleon had to retreat.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Beginning on 19 October and lasting well into December, the French Army faced several overwhelming obstacles on its long retreat: famine, typhus, freezing temperatures, harassing cossacks, and Russian forces barring the way out of the country.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Abandoned by Napoleon in November, the *Grande Armée* was reduced to one-tenth of its original size by the time it reached Poland and relative safety.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] In 1869, the full edition of *War and Peace* by Leo Tolstoy was published.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The novel reported a very accurate description of the Napoleonic invasion of 1812, reviving memories of the Russian resistance.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] This led to the commissioning of new monuments, paintings and also of new musical compositions, including Tchaikovsky's.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Tchaikovsky's friend and mentor Nikolai Rubinstein suggested that he write a grand commemorative piece for use in related festivities.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Tchaikovsky began work on the project on 12 October 1880, finishing it six weeks later.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] However, this performance did not take place, possibly due in part to the over-ambitious plan.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Regardless, the assassination of Alexander II that March deflated much of the impetus for the project.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] In 1882, during the All-Russia Arts and Industry Exhibition, the Overture was performed in a tent next to the unfinished cathedral.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The cathedral was completed on 26 May 1883.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Meanwhile, Tchaikovsky complained to his patron Nadezhda von Meck that he was "... not a conductor of festival pieces," and that the *Overture* would be "... very loud and noisy, but [without] artistic merit, because I wrote it without warmth and without love." He put it together in six weeks.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] It is this work that would make the Tchaikovsky estate exceptionally wealthy, as it is one of the most performed and recorded works from his catalog.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] In Russia, during the Soviet era, the imperial anthem was replaced with the chorus "Glory, Glory to you, holy Rus'!" (*Славься, славься, святая Русь!*), which came from the finale of Mikhail Glinka's opéra *Ivan Susanin*, a historical drama about a patriotic commoner of the same name.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] With the dissolution of the Soviet Union at the end of the Cold War, the original score returned.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] As a rousing patriotic hymn, the Overture has subsequently been adapted into and associated with other contexts than that of the Russian resistance to Napoleon's invasion.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The *1812 Overture* is popularly known in the United States as a symbol of the United States Independence Day, a tradition that dates back to a 1974 choice made by Arthur Fiedler for a performance at the Boston Pops July 4 concert.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] An earlier outdoors July presentation in the U.S. was by the National Symphony Orchestra, led by Howard Mitchell, on 7 July 1950—incorporation eight 75mm Howitzers.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] According to the NSO's management, the performance celebrated the sesquicentennial of the relocation of America's capital from Philadelphia to Washington, DC.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The piece was parodied by composer Malcolm Arnold in *A Grand, Grand Overture* which features four rifles, three Hoover vacuum cleaners (two uprights in B♭ and one horizontal with detachable sucker in C), and an electric floor polisher in E♭; it is dedicated to President Hoover.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Bach for the 1989 musical album *1712 Overture and Other Musical Assaults*.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The piece begins with the simple, plaintive Russian melody of the Eastern Orthodox *Troparion of the Holy Cross* (also known as "O Lord, Save Thy People") played by four cellos and two violas.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] This represents the Russian people praying for the victory.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Then, the French national anthem, "La Marseillaise", is heard, representing the invading French army.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Then, the melody of "La Marseillaise" is heard competing against Russian folk music, representing the two armies fighting each other as the French approached Moscow.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] At this point, five cannon shots are heard, representing the Battle of Borodino.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] This is where "La Marseillaise" is most prominent, and seems to be winning.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] After this, a long descending run represents the French army retreating out of Moscow as the freezing winter winds rage on.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] At the end of this run the opening motif is repeated, which can be interpreted as prayers being answered.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The grand finale culminates with eleven more cannon shots and the melody of "God Save the Tsar!".
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Although La Marseillaise was chosen as the French national anthem in 1795, it was revoked by Napoleon in 1805 and forbidden from being played in his presence, and would certainly not have been played during the Russian campaign.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] It was only reinstated as the French anthem in 1879 – the year before the commission of the overture – which can explain its use by Tchaikovsky in the overture.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] "Chant du départ", nicknamed "the brother of the Marseillaise" by French Republican soldiers, served as the official anthem of Napoleon's regime.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] However, it had been largely forgotten by 1882, while educated Russians of the time were likely to be familiar with the tune of "La Marseillaise" and recognize its significance.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Although "God Save the Tsar!" was the Russian national anthem during Tchaikovsky's lifetime, it did not exist in 1812.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] There was no official Russian anthem until 1815, from which time until 1833 the anthem was "The Prayer of Russians" (*Molitva russkikh*), sung to the tune of "God Save the King".
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The two songs both start with the same words, God Save the Tsar!, but diverge after that.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] In the introduction, the prayer Tropar Krestu (Troparion to the Cross) is used.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] There are four versions of this prayer used in the introduction.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Time lag alone precludes implementation of cues for the shots for fewer than sixteen 1812-era field pieces.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Shortlist of performances of Tchaikovsky's *1812 Overture* during and shortly after his life.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The earliest traceable orchestral recording, which does not include the shots and features no percussion apart from bells, was by the Royal Albert Hall Orchestra conducted by Landon Ronald, and issued by His Master's Voice on three 12-inch 78-rpm sides in 1916.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] A Royal Opera Orchestra recording of about the same time similarly contains no shots at all.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Antal Doráti's 1954 Mercury Records recording with the Minneapolis Symphony Orchestra, partially recorded at West Point, and using the Yale Memorial Carillon in New Haven, Connecticut, uses a Napoleonic French single muzzleloading cannon shot dubbed in 16 times as written.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] On the first edition of the recording, one side played the *Overture* and the other side played a narrative by Deems Taylor about how the cannon and bell effects were accomplished.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] (Later editions placed the commentary after the performance on side 1 and the *Capriccio Italien* on side 2.) A stereophonic version was recorded on 5 April 1958, using the bells of the Laura Spelman Rockefeller Memorial Carillon, at Riverside Church.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] On this Mercury Living Presence Stereo recording, the spoken commentary was also given by Deems Taylor and the 1812 was coupled with Tchaikovsky's *Capriccio Italien*.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Later editions coupled the *1812 Overture* with Dorati's recording of Beethoven's *Wellington's Victory*, which featured the London Symphony Orchestra and real cannon.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The Black Dyke Band has recorded a brass band arrangement of the piece.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] This recording on their album *Symphonic Brass* includes the cannon shots as originally written.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra conducted by Herbert Von Karajan, and the Don Cossacks Choir recorded the piece in 1967 for Deutsche Grammophon.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] In 1971, CBS released a recording with the Philadelphia Orchestra conducted by Eugene Ormandy, also featuring the Mormon Tabernacle Choir, the Valley Forge Military Academy band and real artillery shots.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] British rock drummer Cozy Powell sampled the overture at the end of the track "Over The Top" in his eponymous 1979 studio album.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The first digital recording occurred in 1979 by Telarc with the Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra headlining under the leadership of Erich Kunzel.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The Kiev Symphony Chorus was secured and brought stateside for the express purpose of this recording, while the Children's Choir of Greater Cincinnati (presently doing business as the Cincinnati Youth Choir), a regular Symphony and Pops collaborator to this day, supplied the children's voices.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The recording features the tones of the Emery Memorial Carillon (in adjacent Mariemont, Ohio) to a uniquely magnificent effect alongside high-definition cannon shots using full-sized 19th century military cannons, also specially recorded locally.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] In addition to becoming Telarc's best-selling record and helping to establish them as a company, the record soon became a popular and well-known method for testing hifi record-playing equipment and related setups.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] Only the best and most fine-tuned allowed the cannon shots to be played properly (an accompanying warning for users not to destroy their audio equipment was included with the record).
[src:cannon/1812-overture] In 1989, the Swingle Singers recorded an a cappella version of the overture as part of an album whose title is *1812*.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] In 1990, during a worldwide celebration of the 150th anniversary of Tchaikovsky's birth, the *Overture* was recorded in the city of his youth by the Leningrad Philharmonic Orchestra using 16 muzzleloading cannons fired live as written in the 1880 score.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] That recording was done within earshot of the composer's grave.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The festival was televised for the first time in the United States on 9 March 1991.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The Texan band "The Invincible Czars" released a rock version of *1812 Overture* for the bicentennial of the Battle of Borodino in September 2012.
[src:cannon/1812-overture] The band had already debuted their arrangement of the piece at the 20th annual OK Mozart classical music festival at Bartlesville, Oklahoma, with professional orchestra musicians, in June 2009, complete with fireworks at the finale.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The **1962 Dallas Cowboys season** was their third in the league.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The team finished with a record of 5 wins, 8 losses, and 1 tie, placing them 5th in the NFL's Eastern Conference.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The Cowboys traded away their first-round draft choice (fourth overall) in 1962 NFL draft to the Cleveland Browns.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] With their first selection the Cowboys selected quarterback Sonny Gibbs from Texas Christian University in the second round (eighteenth overall).
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Other notable selections in the draft included defensive end George Andrie from Marquette University in the sixth round and Harold Hays from Southern Mississippi in the fourteenth round.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The team acquired several veterans prior to the 1962 season.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Sam Baker, formerly of the Browns, was acquired to bring stability to the kicker position.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The team traded for offensive tackle Monte Clark from the San Francisco 49ers and acquired Dale Memmelaar, an offensive lineman formerly of the St.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Jerry Norton, an eight-year veteran who had played for the Cardinals and the Philadelphia Eagles, was acquired to help out in the secondary.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Dick Nolan, who had played defensive back for the New York Giants when Cowboys head coach Tom Landry was the defensive coach there, was hired as an assistant coach on the defensive side of the ball, but ended up actually playing safety for most of the season, in addition to coaching.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Lee Folkins, who spent his rookie season with the Green Bay Packers, was the Cowboys starting tight end for most of the year.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Notable rookie free agents the Cowboys signed prior to the season included Pettis Norman, from Johnson C.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Smith University, Mike Gaechter, a track and field athlete as well as a football player, from the University of Oregon, and Cornell Green, a basketball player from Utah State University.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The Cowboys got off to a frustrating start to the 1962 season, as the team was unable to capitalize on opportunities to win their first two games, both played at home.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Head coach Tom Landry decided to alternate between quarterbacks Eddie LeBaron and Don Meredith on every play, and the system proved its worth from the start, as the Cowboys offense rolled up 35 points and 483 yards against the Washington Redskins.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Flanker Frank Clarke caught 10 passes for 241 yards and scored 3 touchdowns in the game, but kicker Sam Baker missed a 35-yard field goal with 13 seconds left and the Cowboys had to settle for a 35–35 tie.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The team rebounded the next week in Los Angeles against the Rams with a 27–17 victory, highlighted by LeBaron's 85-yard touchdown pass to Amos Marsh, but lost a defensive struggle in Cleveland the next week to the Browns 19–10.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The Cowboys, leading the NFL in offense after the first four weeks, went on to score a combined 83 points in their next two games, victories over the Philadelphia Eagles and the Steelers.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The Cowboys were unable to maintain momentum, losing to the struggling St.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Louis Cardinals 28–24 in a sloppily played game, despite Don Perkins rushing for 137 yards.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The Cowboys faced their biggest test of the season the following week against the Eastern Conference-leading New York Giants in front of a record crowd at home, but the Giants won in a rout, 41–10.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Both Eddie LeBaron and Frank Clarke were injured in the game, limiting the Cowboys offense over the next few weeks, and leading to a repeat of the team's late-season tailspin of 1961.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The Cowboys would go on to lose four of the last five games of the season, and while Meredith's inexperience would prove costly at times, it was the defense that was the main culprit, allowing 446 yards or more over five of the last six games.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The lone bright spot of the late season was a 45–21 victory over the Browns in the team's home finale.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Meredith enjoyed his finest day as a professional, throwing two touchdown passes in the first half, and the maligned defense held Browns fullback Jim Brown to just 13 yards.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The Cowboys offense was among the league's best in 1962, finishing second in both yards gained and points scored.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The passing offense finished seventh, and quarterbacks Eddie LeBaron and Don Meredith combined for 31 touchdown passes, second in the league.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] LeBaron earned a trip to the Pro Bowl for his stellar season, his 8.7 yards per pass attempt ranking second overall among quarterbacks.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Frank Clarke emerged as one of the league's top receivers, catching 47 passes for 1043 yards and a league best 14 touchdown receptions, while veteran Billy Howton led the team in receptions with 49.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The rushing game finished second overall with Don Perkins and Amos Marsh combining for 1747 of the Cowboys 2040 rushing yards.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Perkins earned all-pro recognition for his season.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The defense struggled for much of the season, finishing 13th in both yards allowed and points allowed, as the relatively inexperienced players on defense struggled with injuries and the intricacies of Tom Landry's defense.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The team showed improvement from the previous two seasons against the run however, finishing fourth overall and allowing only 3.9 yards per carry.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Against the pass the defense finished last in passing yards allowed, and allowed a league high 16.8 yards per completion.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The pass rush was too often a non-factor, and the defense didn't force as many turnovers as the previous season.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Despite these struggles, the Cowboys did get some strong performances from individual performers such as second-year defensive lineman Bob Lilly, who was named to his first pro bowl, and cornerback Don Bishop, who finished with six interceptions.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Middle linebacker Jerry Tubbs also earned pro bowl recognition.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Veteran Sam Baker improved the team's kicking game from the previous season, averaging 45.4 yards per punt, and converting 14 field goals out of 27 attempts.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Amos Marsh had a solid season returning kickoffs, averaging 25.0 yards per kick return, and returning a kickoff for a score in a victory against the Eagles.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] The team struggled covering kickoff returns, allowing 25.5 yards per kick return, and finding a reliable punt returner was becoming an annual problem.
[src:cannon/1962-dallas-cowboys-season] Tie games were not officially counted in the standings until 1972.
[src:cannon/1962-pittsburgh-steelers-season] The **1962 Pittsburgh Steelers season** marked the franchise's 30th year in the National Football League (NFL).
[src:cannon/1962-pittsburgh-steelers-season] The team finished in second place with 9 wins and 5 losses.
[src:cannon/1962-pittsburgh-steelers-season] The Steelers played in the NFL Playoff Bowl but lost to the Detroit Lions 17–10.
[src:cannon/1962-pittsburgh-steelers-season] The game matched the conference runners-up for third place in the league and was played three weeks after the end of the regular season (and a week after the championship game).
[src:cannon/1962-pittsburgh-steelers-season] The ten editions of the Playoff Bowl, all held at the Orange Bowl in Miami, Florida, are now considered exhibition games by the NFL, not post-season contests.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] The **2007–08 Columbus Blue Jackets season** began October 5, 2007.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] It was the Blue Jackets' eighth season in the National Hockey League (NHL).
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] The Blue Jackets did not qualify for the 2008 Stanley Cup playoffs.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] The Blue Jackets attempted to qualify for the playoffs for the first time in franchise history.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] Scott Howson was hired prior to the 2007 NHL entry draft as the second general manager in team history, replacing Doug MacLean.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] The Blue Jackets finished with a 34–36–12 record, earning 80 points and missing the playoffs.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] The Blue Jackets finished fourth in the Central Division, finishing above the St.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] Louis Blues and 13th in the Western Conference.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] On March 16, 2008, Columbus set a franchise record for points in a season, 75, with a 4–3 win over the Detroit Red Wings in Columbus.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] The Blue Jackets started off the season well with a 7–3–1 record in October, but falling behind in the Western Conference in November with a 4–7–3 record.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] During the All-star break, Rick Nash was selected to participate in the 2008 All-Star Game for the Western Conference.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] He scored a record-breaking goal just 12 seconds into the period.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] Nash scored three goals in the game, yet the Eastern Conference won the game 8–7.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] The Blue Jackets earned average records in December through February, staying within reach of a playoff spot.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] On February 26, Captain Adam Foote was traded to the Colorado Avalanche in exchange for two draft picks.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] Rick Nash was named the new captain of the team.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] In March, the Blue Jackets' chances of playing in the post-season were fading away after a 4–6–3 record due to the injury of starting goaltender Pascal Leclaire.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] After being mathematically eliminated from making the playoffs, the Blue Jackets lost their last three games of the season.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] The Blue Jackets have been involved in the following transactions during the 2007–08 season.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] Columbus' picks at the 2007 NHL entry draft in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:cannon/2007-08-columbus-blue-jackets-season] The Blue Jackets picked 7th overall in front of their hometown crowd.
[src:cannon/25-mm-caliber] The 25 mm round can be used for anti-materiel or anti-personnel purposes.
[src:cannon/25-mm-caliber] In the anti-personnel role, a 25 mm HE round can kill large numbers of opposing troops either in the open or in light fortifications.
[src:cannon/25-mm-caliber] In the anti-materiel role, a 25 mm weapon armed with armor-piercing rounds can disable many types of aircraft and ground vehicles, including some main battle tanks.
[src:cannon/25-mm-caliber] The US military uses 25 mm weapons in their AV-8B Harrier, AC-130 gunship, M2 Bradley, LAV-25, F-35 Lightning II and as a standard ship-based munition in the Mk 38 autocannon.
[src:cannon/25-mm-caliber] Several sub-types of the NATO 25 mm ammunition are available—the most common being armor-piercing, high-explosive, sabot, tracer, and practice rounds.
[src:cannon/25-mm-caliber] Cartridges are usually composed of a combination of the aforementioned categories.
[src:cannon/25-mm-caliber] For example, the M791 is an armor-piercing discarding sabot with tracer (APDS-T) round.
[src:cannon/25-mm-caliber] It is used against lightly armored vehicles, self-propelled artillery, and aerial targets such as helicopters and slow-moving fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] A **cannon** (plural either *cannons* or *cannon*) is a large-caliber gun classified as a type of artillery, which usually launches a projectile using explosive chemical propellant.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Gunpowder ("black powder") was the primary propellant before the invention of smokeless powder during the late 19th century.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Cannons vary in gauge, effective range, mobility, rate of fire, angle of fire and firepower; different forms of cannon combine and balance these attributes in varying degrees, depending on their intended use on the battlefield.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] A cannon is a type of heavy artillery weapon.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The word *cannon* is derived from several languages, in which the original definition can usually be translated as *tube*, *cane*, or *reed*.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The earliest known depiction of cannons may have appeared in Song dynasty China as early as the 12th century; however, solid archaeological and documentary evidence of cannons do not appear until the 13th century.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In 1288, Yuan dynasty troops are recorded to have used hand cannons in combat, and the earliest extant cannon bearing a date of production comes from the same period.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] By the end of the 14th century, cannons were widespread throughout Eurasia.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Cannons were used primarily as anti-infantry weapons until around 1374, when large cannons were recorded to have breached walls for the first time in Europe.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Cannons featured prominently as siege weapons.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In 1464 a 16,000 kg (35,000 lb) cannon known as the Great Turkish Bombard was created in the Ottoman Empire.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Cannons as field artillery became more important after 1453 when cannons broke down the walls of the Roman Empire's capital, with the introduction of limber, which greatly improved cannon maneuverability and mobility.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] European cannons reached their longer, lighter, more accurate, and more efficient "classic form" around 1480.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] This classic European cannon design stayed relatively consistent in form with minor changes until the 1750s.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In the modern era, the term *cannon* has fallen into disuse, replaced by *guns* or *artillery*, if not a more specific term such as howitzer or mortar, except for automatic weapons called autocannons, usually firing explosive shells of larger caliber than machine-gun bullets.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The word *cannon* is derived from the Old Italian word *cannone*, meaning "large tube", which came from the Latin *canna*, in turn originating from the Greek κάννα (*kanna*), "reed", and then generalised to mean any hollow tube-like object.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The word has been used to refer to a gun since 1326 in Italy and 1418 in England.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The plural forms *cannons* and *cannon* are both correct.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The cannon may have appeared as early as the 12th century in China, and was probably a parallel development or evolution of the fire-lance, a short ranged anti-personnel weapon combining a gunpowder-filled tube and a polearm.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Projectiles such as iron scraps or porcelain shards, mixed together with the gunpowder ("co-viative"), were placed in fire lance barrels at some point, and eventually, the paper and bamboo materials of fire lance barrels were replaced by metal.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The earliest known depiction of a cannon is a sculpture from the Dazu Rock Carvings in Sichuan dated to 1128, however, the earliest archaeological samples and textual accounts do not appear until the 13th century.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The primary extant specimens of cannon from the 13th century are the Wuwei Bronze Cannon dated to 1227, the Heilongjiang hand cannon dated to 1288, and the Xanadu Gun dated to 1298.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] However, only the Xanadu gun contains an inscription bearing a date of production, so it is considered the earliest confirmed extant cannon.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The Xanadu Gun is 34.7 cm (13.7 in) in length and weighs 6.2 kg (14 lb).
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The other cannons are dated using contextual evidence.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The Heilongjiang hand cannon is also often considered by some to be the oldest firearm since it was unearthed near the area where the *History of Yuan* reports a battle took place involving hand cannons.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] According to the *History of Yuan*, in 1288, a Jurchen commander by the name of Li Ting led troops armed with hand cannons into battle against the rebel prince Nayan.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Chen Bingying argues there were no guns before 1259, while Dang Shoushan believes the Wuwei gun and other Western Xia era samples point to the appearance of guns by 1220, and Stephen Haw goes even further by stating that guns were developed as early as 1200.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Sinologist Joseph Needham and renaissance siege expert Thomas Arnold provide a more conservative estimate of around 1280 for the appearance of the "true" cannon.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Whether or not any of these are correct, it seems likely that the gun was born sometime during the 13th century.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] References to cannons proliferated throughout China in the following centuries.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In 1341 Xian Zhang wrote a poem called *The Iron Cannon Affair* describing a cannonball fired from an eruptor which could "pierce the heart or belly when striking a man or horse, and even transfix several persons at once." By the 1350s the cannon was used extensively in Chinese warfare.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In 1358 the Ming army failed to take a city due to its garrisons' usage of cannon, however, they themselves would use cannon, in the thousands, later on during the siege of Suzhou in 1366.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The Mongol invasion of Java in 1293 brought gunpowder technology to the Nusantara archipelago in the form of cannon (Chinese: *Pao*).
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] During the Ming dynasty cannons were used in riverine warfare at the Battle of Lake Poyang.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] One shipwreck in Shandong had a cannon dated to 1377 and an anchor dated to 1372.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] From the 13th to 15th centuries cannon-armed Chinese ships also travelled throughout Southeast Asia.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Cannon appeared in Đại Việt by 1390 at the latest.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The first of the western cannon to be introduced were breech-loaders in the early 16th century, which the Chinese began producing themselves by 1523 and improved on by including composite metal construction in their making.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Japan did not acquire cannon until 1510 when a monk brought one back from China, and did not produce any in appreciable numbers.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] During the 1593 siege of Pyongyang, 40,000 Ming troops deployed a variety of cannons against Japanese troops.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Despite their defensive advantage and the use of arquebus by Japanese soldiers, the Japanese were at a severe disadvantage due to their lack of cannon.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Throughout the Japanese invasions of Korea (1592–1598), the Ming–Joseon coalition used artillery widely in land and naval battles, including on the turtle ships of Yi Sun-sin.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] According to Ivan Petlin, the first Russian envoy to Beijing, in September 1619, the city was armed with large cannon with cannonballs weighing more than 30 kg (66 lb).
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Outside of China, the earliest texts to mention gunpowder are Roger Bacon's *Opus Majus* (1267) and *Opus Tertium* in what has been interpreted as references to firecrackers.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In the early 20th century, a British artillery officer proposed that another work tentatively attributed to Bacon, *Epistola de Secretis Operibus Artis et Naturae, et de Nullitate Magiae*, dated to 1247, contained an encrypted formula for gunpowder hidden in the text.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] These claims have been disputed by science historians.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In any case, the formula itself is not useful for firearms or even firecrackers, burning slowly and producing mostly smoke.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] There is a record of a gun in Europe dating to 1322 that was discovered in the nineteenth century, but the artifact has since been lost.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In the same year, another similar illustration showed a darker gun being set off by a group of knights, in another work of de Milemete's, *De secretis secretorum Aristotelis*.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] On 11 February of that same year, the Signoria of Florence appointed two officers to obtain *canones de mettallo* and ammunition for the town's defence.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In the following year a document from the Turin area recorded a certain amount was paid "for the making of a certain instrument or device made by Friar Marcello for the projection of pellets of lead".
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] A reference from 1331 describes an attack mounted by two Germanic knights on Cividale del Friuli, using man-portable gunpowder weapons of some sort.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The 1320s seem to have been the takeoff point for guns in Europe according to most modern military historians.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Scholars suggest that the lack of gunpowder weapons in a well-travelled Venetian's catalogue for a new crusade in 1321 implies that guns were unknown in Europe up until this point, further solidifying the 1320 mark, however more evidence in this area may be forthcoming in the future.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The oldest extant cannon in Europe is a small bronze example unearthed in Loshult, Scania in southern Sweden.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] It dates from the early-mid 14th century, and is currently in the Swedish History Museum in Stockholm.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Early cannons in Europe often shot arrows and were known by an assortment of names such as *pot-de-fer*, *tonnoire*, *ribaldis*, and *büszenpyle*.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The *ribaldis*, which shot large arrows and simplistic grapeshot, were first mentioned in the English Privy Wardrobe accounts during preparations for the Battle of Crécy, between 1345 and 1346.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The Florentine Giovanni Villani recounts their destructiveness, indicating that by the end of the battle, "the whole plain was covered by men struck down by arrows and cannon balls".
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Similar cannon were also used at the siege of Calais (1346–47), although it was not until the 1380s that the *ribaudekin* clearly became mounted on wheels.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The Battle of Crécy which pitted the English against the French in 1346 featured the early use of cannon which helped the longbowmen repulse a large force of Genoese crossbowmen deployed by the French.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The English originally intended to use the cannon against cavalry sent to attack their archers, thinking that the loud noises produced by their cannon would panic the advancing horses along with killing the knights atop them.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Early cannons could also be used for more than simply killing men and scaring horses.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] English cannon were used defensively in 1346 during the siege of Breteuil to launch fire onto an advancing siege tower.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In this way, cannons could be used to burn down siege equipment before it reached the fortifications.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The use of cannons to shoot fire could also be used offensively as another battle involved the setting of a castle ablaze with similar methods.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The particular incendiary used in these projectiles was most likely a gunpowder mixture.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] This is one area where early Chinese and European cannons share a similarity as both were possibly used to shoot fire.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Early European cannons were rather small, dwarfed by the bombards, which would come later.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In fact, it is possible that the cannons used at Crécy were capable of being moved rather quickly as there is an anonymous chronicle that notes the guns being used to attack the French camp, indicating that they would have been mobile enough to press the attack.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] These smaller cannons would eventually give way to larger, wall-breaching guns by the end of the 1300s.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] There is no clear consensus on when the cannon first appeared in the Islamic world, with dates ranging from 1260 to the mid-14th century.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] However, some scholars do not accept these early dates.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] While the date of its first appearance is not entirely clear, the general consensus among most historians is that there is no doubt the Mamluk forces were using cannon by 1342.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Other accounts may have also mentioned the use of cannon in the early 14th century.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] An Arabic text dating to 1320–1350 describes a type of gunpowder weapon called a *midfa* which uses gunpowder to shoot projectiles out of a tube at the end of a stock.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Some scholars consider this a hand cannon while others dispute this claim.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The Nasrid army besieging Elche in 1331 made use of "iron pellets shot with fire".
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] According to historian Ahmad Y. al-Hassan, during the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260, the Mamluks used cannon against the Mongols.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] He claims that this was "the first cannon in history" and used a gunpowder formula almost identical to the ideal composition for explosive gunpowder.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] He also argues that this was not known in China or Europe until much later.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Al-Hassan further claims that the earliest textual evidence of cannon is from the Middle East, based on earlier originals which report hand-held cannons being used by the Mamluks at the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Such an early date is not accepted by some historians, including David Ayalon, Iqtidar Alam Khan, Joseph Needham and Tonio Andrade.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Khan argues that it was the Mongols who introduced gunpowder to the Islamic world, and believes cannon only reached Mamluk Egypt in the 1370s.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Needham argued that the term *midfa*, dated to textual sources from 1342 to 1352, did not refer to true hand-guns or bombards, and that contemporary accounts of a metal-barrel cannon in the Islamic world did not occur until 1365.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Similarly, Andrade dates the textual appearance of cannons in middle eastern sources to the 1360s.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Gabor Ágoston and David Ayalon note that the Mamluks had certainly used siege cannons by 1342 or the 1360s, respectively, but earlier uses of cannons in the Islamic World are vague with a possible appearance in the Emirate of Granada by the 1320s and 1330s, though evidence is inconclusive.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Ibn Khaldun reported the use of cannon as siege machines by the Marinid sultan Abu Yaqub Yusuf at the siege of Sijilmasa in 1274.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The passage by Ibn Khaldun on the Marinid siege of Sijilmassa in 1274 occurs as follows: "[The Sultan] installed siege engines ... and gunpowder engines ..., which project small balls of iron.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] These balls are ejected from a chamber ... placed in front of a kindling fire of gunpowder; this happens by a strange property which attributes all actions to the power of the Creator." The source is not contemporary and was written a century later, around 1382.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Needham believes Ibn Khaldun was speaking of fire lances rather than hand cannon.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The Ottoman Empire made good use of cannon as siege artillery.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Sixty-eight super-sized bombards were used by Mehmed the Conqueror to capture Constantinople in 1453.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Jim Bradbury argues that Urban, a Hungarian cannon engineer, introduced this cannon from Central Europe to the Ottoman realm; according to Paul Hammer, however, it could have been introduced from other Islamic countries which had earlier used cannons.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] These cannons could fire heavy stone balls a mile, and the sound of their blast could reportedly be heard from a distance of 10 miles (16 km).
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Shkodëran historian Marin Barleti discusses Turkish bombards at length in his book *De obsidione Scodrensi* (1504), describing the 1478–79 siege of Shkodra in which eleven bombards and two mortars were employed.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The Ottomans also used cannon to control passage of ships through the Bosphorus strait.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Ottoman cannons also proved effective at stopping crusaders at Varna in 1444 and Kosovo in 1448 despite the presence of European cannon in the former case.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The similar Dardanelles Guns (for the location) were created by Munir Ali in 1464 and were still in use during the Anglo-Turkish War (1807–1809).
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] These were cast in bronze into two parts: the chase (the barrel) and the breech, which combined weighed 18.4 tonnes.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The two parts were screwed together using levers to facilitate moving it.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Fathullah Shirazi, a Persian inhabitant of India who worked for Akbar in the Mughal Empire, developed a volley gun in the 16th century.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] While there is evidence of cannons in Iran as early as 1405 they were not widespread.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] This changed following the increased use of firearms by Shah Ismail I, and the Iranian army used 500 cannons by the 1620s, probably captured from the Ottomans or acquired by allies in Europe.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] By 1443, Iranians were also making some of their own cannon, as Mir Khawand wrote of a 1200 kg metal piece being made by an Iranian *rikhtegar* which was most likely a cannon.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Due to the difficulties of transporting cannon in mountainous terrain, their use was less common compared to their use in Europe.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Documentary evidence of cannons in Russia does not appear until 1382 and they were used only in sieges, often by the defenders.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] It was not until 1475 when Ivan III established the first Russian cannon foundry in Moscow that they began to produce cannons natively.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The earliest surviving cannon from Russia dates to 1485.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Later on, large cannons were known as bombards, ranging from three to five feet in length and were used by Dubrovnik and Kotor in defence during the later 14th century.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The first bombards were made of iron, but bronze became more prevalent as it was recognized as more stable and capable of propelling stones weighing as much as 45 kilograms (99 lb).
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Around the same period, the Byzantine Empire began to accumulate its own cannon to face the Ottoman Empire, starting with medium-sized cannon 3 feet (0.91 m) long and of 10 in calibre.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The earliest reliable recorded use of artillery in the region was against the Ottoman siege of Constantinople in 1396, forcing the Ottomans to withdraw.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The Ottomans acquired their own cannon and laid siege to the Byzantine capital again in 1422.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] By 1453, the Ottomans used 68 Hungarian-made cannon for the 55-day bombardment of the walls of Constantinople, "hurling the pieces everywhere and killing those who happened to be nearby".
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The largest of their cannons was the Great Turkish Bombard, which required an operating crew of 200 men and 70 oxen, and 10,000 men to transport it.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Gunpowder made the formerly devastating Greek fire obsolete, and with the final fall of Constantinople—which was protected by what were once the strongest walls in Europe—on 29 May 1453, "it was the end of an era in more ways than one".
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Cannons were introduced to the Javanese Majapahit Empire when Kublai Khan's Mongol-Chinese army under the leadership of Ike Mese sought to invade Java in 1293.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] *History of Yuan* mentioned that the Mongol used a weapon called *p'ao* against Daha forces.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] This weapon is interpreted differently by researchers, it may be a trebuchet that throws thunderclap bombs, firearms, cannons, or rockets.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] It is possible that the gunpowder weapons carried by the Mongol–Chinese troops amounted to more than one type.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Thomas Stamford Raffles wrote in *The History of Java* that in 1247 saka (1325 AD), cannons were widely used in Java especially by the Majapahit.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] It is recorded that the small kingdoms in Java that sought the protection of Majapahit had to hand over their cannons to the Majapahit.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Majapahit under *Mahapatih* (prime minister) Gajah Mada (in office 1331–1364) utilized gunpowder technology obtained from Yuan dynasty for use in naval fleet.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Mongol-Chinese gunpowder technology of Yuan dynasty resulted in eastern-style cetbang which is similar to Chinese cannon.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Swivel guns however, only developed in the archipelago because of the close maritime relations of the Nusantara archipelago with the territory of West India after 1460 AD, which brought new types of gunpowder weapons to the archipelago, likely through Arab intermediaries.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] This weapon seems to be cannon and gun of Ottoman tradition, for example the prangi, which is a breech-loading swivel gun.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] A new type of cetbang, called the western-style cetbang, was derived from the Turkish prangi.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Just like prangi, this cetbang is a breech-loading swivel gun made of bronze or iron, firing single rounds or scattershots (a large number of small bullets).
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Cannons derived from western-style cetbang can be found in Nusantara, among others were lantaka and lela.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Most lantakas were made of bronze and the earliest ones were breech-loaded.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] There is a trend toward muzzle-loading weapons during colonial times.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] When the Portuguese came to the archipelago, they referred to the breech-loading swivel gun as *berço*, while the Spaniards call it *verso*.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] A pole gun (*bedil tombak*) was recorded as being used by Java in 1413.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] 1514 said that the inhabitants of Java were great masters in casting artillery and very good artillerymen.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] They made many one-pounder cannon (*cetbang* or *rentaka*), long muskets, *spingarde* (arquebus), *schioppi* (hand cannon), Greek fire, guns (cannon), and other fireworks.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Every place was considered excellent in casting artillery, and in the knowledge of using it.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In 1513, the Javanese fleet led by Pati Unus sailed to attack Portuguese Malacca "with much artillery made in Java, for the Javanese are skilled in founding and casting, and in all works in iron, over and above what they have in India".
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] By early 16th century, the Javanese already locally-producing large guns, some of them still survived until the present day and dubbed as "sacred cannon" or "holy cannon".
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] These cannons varied between 180- and 260-pounders, weighing anywhere between 3 and 8 tons, length of them between 3 and 6 m (9.8 and 19.7 ft).
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Cannons were used by the Ayutthaya Kingdom in 1352 during its invasion of the Khmer Empire.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Within a decade large quantities of gunpowder could be found in the Khmer Empire.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] By the end of the 14th century firearms were also used by the Trần dynasty.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Saltpeter harvesting was recorded by Dutch and German travellers as being common in even the smallest villages and was collected from the decomposition process of large dung hills specifically piled for the purpose.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The Dutch punishment for possession of non-permitted gunpowder appears to have been amputation.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Ownership and manufacture of gunpowder was later prohibited by the colonial Dutch occupiers.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] According to colonel McKenzie quoted in Sir Thomas Stamford Raffles' *The History of Java* (1817), the purest sulfur was supplied from a crater from a mountain near the straits of Bali.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In Africa, the Adal Sultanate and the Abyssinian Empire both deployed cannons during the Adal-Abyssinian War.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Imported from Arabia, and the wider Islamic world, the Adalites led by Ahmed ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi were the first African power to introduce cannon warfare to the African continent.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Later on as the Portuguese Empire entered the war it would supply and train the Abyssinians with cannons, while the Ottoman Empire sent soldiers and cannon to back Adal.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] The conflict proved, through their use on both sides, the value of firearms such as the matchlock musket, cannon, and the arquebus over traditional weapons.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] While previous smaller guns could burn down structures with fire, larger and more powerful cannons forced engineers to develop stronger castle walls from enemy attacks.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Cannons were used for other purposes, as fortifications began using cannons as defensive instruments.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In India, the fort of Raicher had gun ports built into its walls to accommodate the use of defensive cannons.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In *The Art of War*, Niccolò Machiavelli opined that field artillery forced an army to take up a defensive posture and opposed a more ideal offensive stance.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Machiavelli's concerns can be seen in the criticisms of Portuguese mortars being used in India during the sixteenth century as lack of mobility was one of the key problems with the design.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] In Russia the early cannons were again placed in forts as a defensive tool.
[src:cannon/cannon-p01] Cannons were also difficult to move around in mountainous regions; offensives conducted with such weapons would often be unsuccessful in areas such as Iran.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] By the 16th century, cannons were made in a great variety of lengths and bore diameters, but the general rule was that the longer the barrel, the longer the range.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Some cannons made during this time had barrels exceeding 10 ft (3.0 m) in length, and could weigh up to 20,000 pounds (9,100 kg).
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Consequently, large amounts of gunpowder were needed to allow them to fire stone balls several hundred yards.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] By mid-century, European monarchs began to classify cannons to reduce the confusion.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Henry II of France opted for six sizes of cannon, but others settled for more; the Spanish used twelve sizes, and the English sixteen.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] They are, from largest to smallest: the cannon royal, cannon, cannon serpentine, bastard cannon, demicannon, pedrero, culverin, basilisk, demiculverin, bastard culverin, saker, minion, falcon, falconet, serpentine, and rabinet.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Better powder had been developed by this time as well.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Instead of the finely ground powder used by the first bombards, powder was replaced by a "corned" variety of coarse grains.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] This coarse powder had pockets of air between grains, allowing fire to travel through and ignite the entire charge quickly and uniformly.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The end of the Middle Ages saw the construction of larger, more powerful cannon, as well as their spread throughout the world.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] As they were not effective at breaching the newer fortifications resulting from the development of cannon, siege engines—such as siege towers and trebuchets—became less widely used.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] However, wooden "battery-towers" took on a similar role as siege towers in the gunpowder age—such as that used at Siege of Kazan in 1552, which could hold ten large-calibre cannon, in addition to 50 lighter pieces.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Another notable effect of cannon on warfare during this period was the change in conventional fortifications.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Niccolò Machiavelli wrote, "There is no wall, whatever its thickness that artillery will not destroy in only a few days." Although castles were not immediately made obsolete by cannon, their use and importance on the battlefield rapidly declined.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Instead of majestic towers and merlons, the walls of new fortresses were thick, angled, and sloped, while towers became low and stout; increasing use was also made of earth and brick in breastworks and redoubts.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] These new defences became known as bastion forts, after their characteristic shape which attempted to force any advance towards it directly into the firing line of the guns.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] A few of these featured cannon batteries, such as the House of Tudor's Device Forts in England.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Bastion forts soon replaced castles in Europe and, eventually, those in the Americas as well.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] By the end of the 15th century, several technological advancements made cannons more mobile.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Wheeled gun carriages and trunnions became common, and the invention of the limber further facilitated transportation.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] As a result, field artillery became more viable and began to see more widespread use, often alongside the larger cannons intended for sieges.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Better gunpowder, cast-iron projectiles (replacing stone), and the standardisation of calibres meant that even relatively light cannons could be deadly.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Despite the increased maneuverability, however, cannon were still the slowest component of the army: a heavy English cannon required 23 horses to transport, while a culverin needed nine.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Even with this many animals pulling, they still moved at a walking pace.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Due to their relatively slow speed, lack of organisation, and undeveloped tactics, the combination of pike and shot still dominated the battlefields of Europe.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Innovations continued, notably the German invention of the mortar, a thick-walled, short-barrelled gun that blasted shot upward at a steep angle.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Mortars were useful for sieges, as they could hit targets behind walls or other defences.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] This cannon found more use with the Dutch, who learnt to shoot bombs filled with powder from them.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] "Single firing" was first used to ignite the fuse, where the bomb was placed with the fuse down against the cannon's propellant.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] This often resulted in the fuse being blown into the bomb, causing it to blow up as it left the mortar.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Because of this, "double firing" was tried where the gunner lit the fuse and then the touch hole.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] This required considerable skill and timing, and was especially dangerous if the gun misfired, leaving a lighted bomb in the barrel.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Not until 1650 was it accidentally discovered that double-lighting was superfluous as the heat of firing would light the fuse.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Gustavus Adolphus of Sweden emphasised the use of light cannon and mobility in his army, and created new formations and tactics that revolutionised artillery.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] He discontinued using all 12 pounder—or heavier—cannon as field artillery, preferring, instead, to use cannons that could be handled by only a few men.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] One obsolete type of gun, the "leatheren", was replaced by 4 pounder and 9 pounder demi-culverins.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] These could be operated by three men, and pulled by only two horses.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Gustavus Adolphus's army was also the first to use a cartridge that contained both powder and shot which sped up reloading, increasing the rate of fire.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Finally, against infantry he pioneered the use of canister shot—essentially a tin can filled with musket balls.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Until then there was no more than one cannon for every thousand infantrymen on the battlefield but Gustavus Adolphus increased the number of cannons sixfold.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Each regiment was assigned two pieces, though he often arranged them into batteries instead of distributing them piecemeal.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] He used these batteries to break his opponent's infantry line, while his cavalry would outflank their heavy guns.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] At the Battle of Breitenfeld, in 1631, Adolphus proved the effectiveness of the changes made to his army, by defeating Johann Tserclaes, Count of Tilly.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Although severely outnumbered, the Swedes were able to fire between three and five times as many volleys of artillery, and their infantry's linear formations helped ensure they did not lose any ground.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Battered by cannon fire, and low on morale, Tilly's men broke ranks and fled.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] In England, cannons were being used to besiege various fortified buildings during the English Civil War.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Nathaniel Nye is recorded as testing a Birmingham cannon in 1643 and experimenting with a saker in 1645.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] From 1645 he was the master gunner to the Parliamentarian garrison at Evesham and in 1646 he successfully directed the artillery at the Siege of Worcester, detailing his experiences and in his 1647 book *The Art of Gunnery*.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Believing that war was as much a science as an art, his explanations focused on triangulation, arithmetic, theoretical mathematics, and cartography as well as practical considerations such as the ideal specification for gunpowder or slow matches.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] His book acknowledged mathematicians such as Robert Recorde and Marcus Jordanus as well as earlier military writers on artillery such as Niccolò Fontana Tartaglia and Thomas (or Francis) Malthus (author of *A Treatise on Artificial Fire-Works*).
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Around this time also came the idea of aiming the cannon to hit a target.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Gunners controlled the range of their cannons by measuring the angle of elevation, using a "gunner's quadrant".
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Cannons did not have sights; therefore, even with measuring tools, aiming was still largely guesswork.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] In the latter half of the 17th century, the French engineer Sébastien Le Prestre de Vauban introduced a more systematic and scientific approach to attacking gunpowder fortresses, in a time when many field commanders "were notorious dunces in siegecraft".
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Careful sapping forward, supported by enfilading ricochets, was a key feature of this system, and it even allowed Vauban to calculate the length of time a siege would take.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] He was also a prolific builder of bastion forts, and did much to popularize the idea of "depth in defence" in the face of cannon.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] These principles were followed into the mid-19th century, when changes in armaments necessitated greater depth defence than Vauban had provided for.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] It was only in the years prior to World War I that new works began to break radically away from his designs.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The lower tier of 17th-century English ships of the line were usually equipped with demi-cannons, guns that fired a 32-pound (15 kg) solid shot, and could weigh up to 3,400 pounds (1,500 kg).
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Demi-cannons were capable of firing these heavy metal balls with such force that they could penetrate more than a metre of solid oak, from a distance of 90 m (300 ft), and could dismast even the largest ships at close range.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Full cannon fired a 42-pound (19 kg) shot, but were discontinued by the 18th century, as they were too unwieldy.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] By the end of the 18th century, principles long adopted in Europe specified the characteristics of the Royal Navy's cannon, as well as the acceptable defects, and their severity.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The United States Navy tested guns by measuring them, firing them two or three times—termed "proof by powder"—and using pressurized water to detect leaks.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The carronade was adopted by the Royal Navy in 1779; the lower muzzle velocity of the round shot when fired from this cannon was intended to create more wooden splinters when hitting the structure of an enemy vessel, as they were believed to be more deadly than the ball by itself.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The carronade was much shorter, and weighed between a third to a quarter of the equivalent long gun; for example, a 32-pounder carronade weighed less than a ton, compared with a 32-pounder long gun, which weighed over 3 t (3.0 long tons; 3.3 short tons).
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The guns were, therefore, easier to handle, and also required less than half as much gunpowder, allowing fewer men to crew them.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Carronades were manufactured in the usual naval gun calibres, but were not counted in a ship of the line's rated number of guns.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] As a result, the classification of Royal Navy vessels in this period can be misleading, as they often carried more cannons than were listed.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Cannons were crucial in Napoleon's rise to power, and continued to play an important role in his army in later years.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] During the French Revolution, the unpopularity of the Directory led to riots and rebellions.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] When over 25,000 royalists led by General Danican assaulted Paris, Paul Barras was appointed to defend the capital; outnumbered five to one and disorganised, the Republicans were desperate.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] When Napoleon arrived, he reorganised the defences but realised that without cannons the city could not be held.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] He ordered Joachim Murat to bring the guns from the Sablons artillery park; the Major and his cavalry fought their way to the recently captured cannons, and brought them back to Napoleon.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] When Danican's poorly trained men attacked, on 13 Vendémiaire 1795 (5 October in the calendar used in France at the time), Napoleon ordered his cannon to fire grapeshot into the mob, an act that became known as the "whiff of grapeshot".
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The slaughter effectively ended the threat to the new government, while, at the same time, making Bonaparte a famous—and popular—public figure.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Among the first generals to recognise that artillery was not being used to its full potential, Napoleon often massed his cannon into batteries and introduced several changes into the French artillery, improving it significantly and making it among the finest in Europe.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Such tactics were successfully used by the French, for example, at the Battle of Friedland, when 66 guns fired a total of 3,000 roundshot and 500 rounds of grapeshot, inflicting severe casualties to the Russian forces, whose losses numbered over 20,000 killed and wounded, in total.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] At the Battle of Waterloo—Napoleon's final battle—the French army had many more artillery pieces than either the British or Prussians.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] As the battlefield was muddy, recoil caused cannons to bury themselves into the ground after firing, resulting in slow rates of fire, as more effort was required to move them back into an adequate firing position; also, roundshot did not ricochet with as much force from the wet earth.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Despite the drawbacks, sustained artillery fire proved deadly during the engagement, especially during the French cavalry attack.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The British infantry, having formed infantry squares, took heavy losses from the French guns, while their own cannons fired at the cuirassiers and lancers, when they fell back to regroup.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Eventually, the French ceased their assault, after taking heavy losses from the British cannon and musket fire.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] In the 1810s and 1820s, greater emphasis was placed on the accuracy of long-range gunfire, and less on the weight of a broadside.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Around 1822, George Marshall wrote *Marshall's Practical Marine Gunnery*.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The book was used by cannon operators in the United States Navy throughout the 19th century.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] It listed all the types of cannons and instructions.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The carronade, although initially very successful and widely adopted, disappeared from the Royal Navy in the 1850s after the development of wrought-iron-jacketed steel cannon by William Armstrong and Joseph Whitworth.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Nevertheless, carronades were used in the American Civil War.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Western cannons during the 19th century became larger, more destructive, more accurate, and could fire at longer range.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] One example is the American 3-inch (76 mm) wrought-iron, muzzle-loading rifle, or Griffen gun (usually called the 3-inch Ordnance Rifle), used during the American Civil War, which had an effective range of over 1.1 mi (1.8 km).
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Another is the smoothbore 12-pounder Napoleon, which originated in France in 1853 and was widely used by both sides in the American Civil War.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] This cannon was renowned for its sturdiness, reliability, firepower, flexibility, relatively lightweight, and range of 1,700 m (5,600 ft).
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The practice of rifling—casting spiralling lines inside the cannon's barrel—was applied to artillery more frequently by 1855, as it gave cannon projectiles gyroscopic stability, which improved their accuracy.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] One of the earliest rifled cannons was the breech-loading Armstrong Gun—also invented by William Armstrong—which boasted significantly improved range, accuracy, and power than earlier weapons.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The projectile fired from the Armstrong gun could reportedly pierce through a ship's side and explode inside the enemy vessel, causing increased damage and casualties.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The British military adopted the Armstrong gun, and was impressed; the Duke of Cambridge even declared that it "could do everything but speak".
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Despite being significantly more advanced than its predecessors, the Armstrong gun was rejected soon after its integration, in favour of the muzzle-loading pieces that had been in use before.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] While both types of gun were effective against wooden ships, neither had the capability to pierce the armour of ironclads; due to reports of slight problems with the breeches of the Armstrong gun, and their higher cost, the older muzzle-loaders were selected to remain in service instead.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The superior cannon of the Western world brought them tremendous advantages in warfare.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] For example, in the First Opium War in China, during the 19th century, British battleships bombarded the coastal areas and fortifications from afar, safe from the reach of the Chinese cannons.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Similarly, the shortest war in recorded history, the Anglo-Zanzibar War of 1896, was brought to a swift conclusion by shelling from British cruisers.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Cannons in the 20th and 21st centuries are usually divided into sub-categories and given separate names.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Some of the most widely used types of modern cannon are howitzers, mortars, guns, and autocannon, although a few very large-calibre cannon, custom-designed, have also been constructed.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Nuclear artillery was experimented with, but was abandoned as impractical.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Modern artillery is used in a variety of roles, depending on its type.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] According to NATO, the general role of artillery is to provide fire support, which is defined as "the application of fire, coordinated with the manoeuvre of forces to destroy, neutralize, or suppress the enemy".
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] When referring to cannons, the term *gun* is often used incorrectly.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] By the early 20th century, infantry weapons had become more powerful, forcing most artillery away from the front lines.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Despite the change to indirect fire, cannons proved highly effective during World War I, directly or indirectly causing over 75% of casualties.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The onset of trench warfare after the first few months of World War I greatly increased the demand for howitzers, as they were more suited to hitting targets in trenches.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Furthermore, their shells carried more explosives than those of guns, and caused considerably less barrel wear.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The German army had the advantage here as they began the war with many more howitzers than the French.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] World War I also saw the use of the Paris Gun, the longest-ranged gun ever fired.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] This 200 mm (8 in) calibre gun was used by the Germans against Paris and could hit targets more than 122 km (76 mi) away.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The Second World War sparked new developments in cannon technology.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Among them were sabot rounds, hollow-charge projectiles, and proximity fuses, all of which increased the effectiveness of cannon against specific targets.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The proximity fuse emerged on the battlefields of Europe in late December 1944.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Used to great effect in anti-aircraft projectiles, proximity fuses were fielded in both the European and Pacific Theatres of Operations; they were particularly useful against V-1 flying bombs and kamikaze planes.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Although widely used in naval warfare, and in anti-air guns, both the British and Americans feared unexploded proximity fuses would be reverse engineered, leading to them limiting their use in continental battles.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] During the Battle of the Bulge, however, the fuses became known as the American artillery's "Christmas present" for the German army because of their effectiveness against German personnel in the open, when they frequently dispersed attacks.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Anti-tank guns were also tremendously improved during the war: in 1939, the British used primarily 2 pounder and 6 pounder guns.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] By the end of the war, 17 pounders had proven much more effective against German tanks, and 32 pounders had entered development.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Meanwhile, German tanks were continuously upgraded with better main guns, in addition to other improvements.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] For example, the Panzer III was originally designed with a 37 mm gun, but was mass-produced with a 50 mm cannon.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] To counter the threat of the Russian T-34s, another, more powerful 50 mm gun was introduced, only to give way to a larger 75 mm cannon, which was in a fixed mount as the StuG III, the most-produced German World War II armoured fighting vehicle of any type.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Despite the improved guns, production of the Panzer III was ended in 1943, as the tank still could not match the T-34, and was replaced by the Panzer IV and Panther tanks.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] In 1944, the 8.8 cm KwK 43 and many variations, entered service with the Wehrmacht, and was used as both a tank main gun, and as the PaK 43 anti-tank gun.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] One of the most powerful guns to see service in World War II, it was capable of destroying any Allied tank at very long ranges.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Despite being designed to fire at trajectories with a steep angle of descent, howitzers can be fired directly, as was done by the 11th Marine Regiment at the Battle of Chosin Reservoir, during the Korean War.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Two field batteries fired directly upon a battalion of Chinese infantry; the Marines were forced to brace themselves against their howitzers, as they had no time to dig them in.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The Chinese infantry took heavy casualties, and were forced to retreat.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The tendency to create larger calibre cannons during the World Wars has reversed since.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The United States Army, for example, sought a lighter, more versatile howitzer, to replace their aging pieces.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] As it could be towed, the M198 was selected to be the successor to the World War II–era cannons used at the time, and entered service in 1979.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Still in use today, the M198 is, in turn, being slowly replaced by the M777 Ultralightweight howitzer, which weighs nearly half as much and can be more easily moved.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Although land-based artillery such as the M198 are powerful, long-ranged, and accurate, naval guns have not been neglected, despite being much smaller than in the past, and, in some cases, having been replaced by cruise missiles.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] However, the *Zumwalt*-class destroyer's planned armament included the Advanced Gun System (AGS), a pair of 155 mm guns, which fire the Long Range Land-Attack Projectile.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The warhead, which weighed 24 pounds (11 kg), had a circular error of probability of 50 m (160 ft), and was mounted on a rocket, to increase the effective range to 100 nmi (190 km), further than that of the Paris Gun.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The AGS's barrels would be water-cooled, and fire 10 rounds per minute, per gun.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The combined firepower from both turrets would give a *Zumwalt*-class destroyer the firepower equivalent to 12 conventional M198 howitzers.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The reason for the re-integration of cannons as a main armament in United States Navy ships was because satellite-guided munitions fired from a gun would be less expensive than a cruise missile but have a similar guidance capability.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Autocannons automatically fire a series of projectiles, similarly to a machine gun.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] They have mechanisms to automatically load their ammunition, and have a high rate of fire often approaching, or, in the case of rotary autocannons, even surpassing the firing rate of a machine gun.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Autocannons are usually of larger calibre than machine guns, typically 20 mm (0.8 in) or greater, and can usually fire explosive shells, unlike machine guns.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Explosive ammunition weighing less than 400 grams, as used by machine-gun calibres, is additionally banned in international conflict for parties to the Saint Petersburg Declaration of 1868.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Most nations use rapid-fire cannon on light vehicles, instead of a more powerful, but heavier, tank gun with a low rate of fire.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] A typical autocannon is the 25 mm US "Bushmaster" chain gun, mounted on the LAV-25 and M2 Bradley armoured vehicles.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The typical rate of fire for a modern autocannon ranges from 90 to 1,800 rounds per minute; systems with multiple barrels, such as rotary autocannon, can have rates of fire of several thousand rounds per minute.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The fastest of these is the GSh-6-23, which has a rate of fire of over 10,000 rounds per minute.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Autocannons are often fitted in aircraft and as shipboard anti-aircraft weapons, as they provide greater destructive power than previously-used machine guns.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The first documented installation of a cannon firing explosive shells on an aircraft was on the Voisin Canon in 1911, displayed at the Paris Exposition that year.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] By World War I, all of the major powers were experimenting with aircraft-mounted cannons; however, their low rate of fire and great size and weight precluded any of them from being anything other than experimental.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The most successful (or least unsuccessful) was the SPAD 12 Ca.1 single-seat fighter with a single 37 mm Puteaux mounted to fire between the cylinder banks and through the propeller boss of the aircraft's Hispano-Suiza 8C engine.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The pilot (by necessity an ace) had to manually load one round at a time.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The first autocannon were developed during World War I as anti-aircraft guns, and one of these, the Coventry Ordnance Works "COW 37 mm gun", was installed in an aircraft.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] However, the war ended before it could be given a field trial, and it never became standard equipment in a production aircraft.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Later trials had it fixed at a steep angle upwards in both the Vickers Type 161 and the Westland C.O.W.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Gun Fighter, an idea that returned later.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] During this period autocannons became available, and several fighters of the German *Luftwaffe* and the Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service were fitted with 20 mm cannons.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] They continued to be installed as an adjunct to machine guns rather than as a replacement, as the rate of fire was too low and each gun was too heavy.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] There was some debate in the RAF as to whether the greater number of possible rounds being fired from a machine gun, or a smaller number of explosive rounds from a cannon was preferable.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Improvements during the war in regards to rate of fire allowed the cannon to displace the machine gun almost entirely.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Cannons were more effective than machine-guns against armour, so they came increasingly into use in World War II; newer fighter aircraft such as the Hawker Tempest usually carried two or four instead of the six to twelve machine guns of earlier aircraft.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The Hispano-Suiza HS.404, Oerlikon 20 mm cannon, MG FF, and their numerous variants became among the most widely used autocannon in the war.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Aircraft cannons, as with machine guns, were either fixed to fire forwards (mounted in the wings, in the nose or fuselage, or in a pannier under either), typically on manoeuvrable fighters, or mounted movably in manned gun turrets on heavier less agile aircraft such as bombers.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Both the Germans and Japanese mounted cannons to fire upwards and forwards for use against heavy bombers, with the Germans calling guns so-installed *Schräge Musik*, derived from a German colloquialism for jazz music—*schräg* means "off-key".
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Nearly all modern fighter aircraft are armed with an autocannon, and they are also commonly fitted on ground-attack aircraft.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] One of the most powerful examples is the 30mm GAU-8/A Avenger Gatling-type rotary cannon mounted on the Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The Lockheed AC-130 gunship, based on a transport aircraft, can carry a 105 mm howitzer and a variety of autocannons ranging up to 40 mm.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Both are used in the close air support role.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Cannons in general have the form of a truncated cone with an internal cylindrical bore for holding an explosive charge and a projectile.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The thickest, strongest, and closed part of the cone is located near the explosive charge.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] As any explosive charge will dissipate in all directions equally, the thickest portion of the cannon is useful for containing and directing this force.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Field artillery cannon in Europe and the Americas were initially made most often of bronze, though later forms were constructed of cast iron and eventually steel.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] However, cast-iron cannon have a tendency to burst without having shown any previous weakness or wear, and this makes them more dangerous to operate.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The older and more-stable forms of cannon were muzzle-loading as opposed to breech-loading—to be used they had to have their ordnance packed down the bore through the muzzle rather than inserted through the breech.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The following terms refer to the components or aspects of a classical western cannon (c.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] In what follows, the words *near*, *close*, and *behind* will refer to those parts towards the thick, closed end of the piece, and *far*, *front*, *in front of*, and *before* to the thinner, open end.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] is determined by the diameter of its bore.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] made of copper screwed into the length of the vent.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The main body of a cannon consists of three basic extensions: the foremost and the longest is called the *chase*, the middle portion is the *reinforce*, and the closest and briefest portion is the *cascabel* or *cascable*.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The chase is simply the entire conical part of the cannon in front of the *reinforce*.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] the narrowest part of the chase, always located near the foremost end of the piece.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] these are a second series of such rings located at the near end of the chase.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] To pack a muzzle-loading cannon, first gunpowder is poured down the bore.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] This is followed by a layer of wadding (often nothing more than paper), and then the cannonball itself.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] A certain amount of windage (in this case meaning that the bore is designed slightly wider than the cannonball) allows the ball to fit down the bore, though the greater the windage the less efficient the propulsion of the ball when the gunpowder is ignited.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] To fire the cannon, the fuse located in the vent is lit, quickly burning down to the gunpowder, which then explodes violently, propelling wadding and ball down the bore and out of the muzzle.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] A small portion of exploding gas also escapes through the vent, but this does not dramatically affect the total force exerted on the ball.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] *Gun* in this context specifically refers to a type of cannon that fires projectiles at high speeds, and usually at relatively low angles; they have been used in warships, and as field artillery.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The term *cannon* is also used for autocannon, a modern repeating weapon firing explosive projectiles.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Cannon have been used extensively in fighter aircraft since World War II.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] In the 1770s, cannon operation worked as follows: each cannon would be manned by two gunners, six soldiers, and four officers of artillery.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The right gunner was to prime the piece and load it with powder, and the left gunner would fetch the powder from the magazine and be ready to fire the cannon at the officer's command.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] On each side of the cannon, three soldiers stood, to ram and sponge the cannon, and hold the ladle.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The second soldier on the left was tasked with providing 50 bullets.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Before loading, the cannon would be cleaned with a wet sponge to extinguish any smouldering material from the last shot.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Fresh powder could be set off prematurely by lingering ignition sources.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The powder was added, followed by wadding of paper or hay, and the ball was placed in and rammed down.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] After ramming, the cannon would be aimed with the elevation set using a quadrant and a plummet.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] At 45 degrees, the ball had the utmost range: about ten times the gun's level range.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Any angle above a horizontal line was called random-shot.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Wet sponges were used to cool the pieces every ten or twelve rounds.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] During the Napoleonic Wars, a British gun team consisted of five gunners to aim it, clean the bore with a damp sponge to quench any remaining embers before a fresh charge was introduced, and another to load the gun with a bag of powder and then the projectile.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The fourth gunner pressed his thumb on the vent hole, to prevent a draught that might fan a flame.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The charge loaded, the fourth would prick the bagged charge through the vent hole, and fill the vent with powder.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] On command, the fifth gunner would fire the piece with a slow match.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Friction primers replaced slow match ignition by the mid-19th century.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] When a cannon had to be abandoned such as in a retreat or surrender, the touch hole of the cannon would be plugged flush with an iron spike, disabling the cannon (at least until metal boring tools could be used to remove the plug).
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] A gun was said to be *honeycombed* when the surface of the bore had cavities, or holes in it, caused by corrosion or casting defects.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] In the United States, muzzleloading cannons made before 1899 (and replicas) that are unable to fire fixed ammunition are considered antiques.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] They are not subject to the Gun Control Act of 1968 or National Firearms Act of 1934.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] They may be subject to local rules in some jurisdictions, however.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Historically, logs or poles have been used as decoys to mislead the enemy as to the strength of an emplacement.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The "Quaker Gun trick" was used by Colonel William Washington's Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War; in 1780, approximately 100 Loyalists surrendered to them, rather than face bombardment.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] During the American Civil War, Quaker guns were also used by the Confederates, to compensate for their shortage of artillery.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The decoy cannon were painted black at the "muzzle", and positioned behind fortifications to delay Union attacks on those positions.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] On occasion, real gun carriages were used to complete the deception.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Cannon sounds have sometimes been used in classical pieces with a military theme.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] One of the best known examples is Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky's *1812 Overture*.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The overture is to be performed using an artillery section together with the orchestra, resulting in noise levels high enough that musicians are required to wear ear protection.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The cannon fire simulates Russian artillery bombardments of the Battle of Borodino, a critical battle in Napoleon's invasion of Russia, whose defeat the piece celebrates.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] When the overture was first performed, the cannon were fired by an electric current triggered by the conductor.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] However, the overture was not recorded with real cannon fire until Mercury Records and conductor Antal Doráti's 1958 recording of the Minnesota Orchestra.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Cannon fire is also frequently used in presentations of the *1812* on American Independence Day, a tradition started by Arthur Fiedler of the Boston Pops in 1974.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The hard rock band AC/DC used cannon fire in their song "For Those About to Rock (We Salute You)", and in live shows replica Napoleonic cannons and pyrotechnics were used to perform the piece.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] A recording of that song has accompanied the firing of an authentic reproduction of a M1857 12-pounder Napoleon during Columbus Blue Jackets goal celebrations at Nationwide Arena since opening night of the 2007–08 season.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The cannon is the focal point of the team's alternate logo on its third jerseys.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Cannons have been fired in touchdown celebrations by several American football teams including the San Diego Chargers.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The Pittsburgh Steelers used one only during the 1962 campaign but discontinued it after Buddy Dial was startled by inadvertently running face-first into the cannon's smoky discharge in a 42–27 loss to the Dallas Cowboys.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Cannon recovered from the sea are often extensively damaged from exposure to salt water; electrolytic reduction treatment is required to forestall corrosion.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] The cannon is then washed in deionized water to remove the electrolyte, and is treated in tannic acid, which prevents further rust and gives the metal a bluish-black colour.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] Cannon on display may be protected from oxygen and moisture by a wax sealant.
[src:cannon/cannon-p02] A coat of polyurethane may also be painted over the wax sealant, to prevent the cannon from attracting dust.
